# Slice 8 — Subject-period attendance (opt-in): plan + cp1
_(plan-first agreed 2026-06-08; cp1 built into 2026-06-09 as the clock rolled —
kept here with the plan it implements.)_

## Cp split (2 cps)
- **cp1 (this):** model + `School.subjectAttendanceEnabled` column + migration +
  RLS (22→23) + `SubjectAttendanceService` (register/mark/summary) + opt-in flag
  wired into the existing `PATCH /schools/me` + 3 endpoints + integration spec.
- **cp2:** `/teacher/attendance/subject` register + summary UI + the
  `/settings/attendance` owner/admin toggle + manual browser pass.

## The 7 questions — resolved
- **Q1 period** — Int, min 1, no upper bound (spec-canonical).
- **Q2 toggle** — extended `PATCH /schools/me` (owner+admin per acceptance #9
  "admin toggles"), `subjectAttendanceEnabled` added to `patchSchoolSchema` +
  `SchoolMeDto`; existing `school.update` audit captures it. NO new endpoint /
  audit action / role gate. (My plan-first instinct to make it owner-only +
  a new `/schools/me/settings` was wrong — see banking #1, #2.)
- **Q3 scope gate** — inline private `assertCanMarkSubject` on
  `getTeacherScope`, mirroring slice 7's `assertCanAccessArmAttendance`. NOT
  promoted to a shared util (one consumer — see banking #3).
- **Q4 summary** — aggregate by PERIOD record; rate = (PRESENT+LATE)/periodsMarked
  × 10000, EXCUSED in the denominator (policy i).
- **Q5 summary scope** — subject teacher sees only subjects they teach
  (symmetric with the mark gate); owner/admin see all.
- **Q6 dev-seed** — leaves `subjectAttendanceEnabled` default **false**; the cp2
  manual scenario 1 toggles it on (tests the full hidden→toggle→surface
  lifecycle). No non-default config baked into the seed (banking #4).
- **Q7 cp split** — 2 cps confirmed.

## Spec deviations (justified, noted in the cp1 commit body)
- **Routes** `/subject-attendance/{register,mark,summary}` (spec canon), a
  top-level module — NOT nested under `/attendance`.
- **Summary params** include `classArmId` despite the spec's abbreviated
  `?subjectId=&termId=` — the per-arm summary mirrors slice 7 and is the
  consumable view (a subject spans arms).
- **Schema** spec-verbatim (field order `studentId` before `classArmId`, bare
  `@@index([schoolId])` kept) **plus** one arm-keyed summary index
  `[schoolId, classArmId, subjectId, termId]` mirroring slice 7's term index.
  The two long indexes needed explicit `map:` names — their auto-names both
  truncate to the same 63-char Postgres identifier and collide.

## Banking patterns (carried into the cp1 commit body)
1. **Spec role gates are intentional.** When the spec specifies owner+admin
   (acceptance #9 "admin toggles"), plan-first shouldn't *tighten* it without an
   explicit reason. My instinct to make the toggle owner-only was wrong.
2. **Reuse over invention.** The existing `PATCH /schools/me` is the right path
   for a new `School` field. New endpoints need a justification — a different
   gate, audit shape, or consumer. `subjectAttendanceEnabled` has none, so
   extension wins.
3. **Don't pre-extract for a single consumer.** A shared util needs two
   consumers minimum. Slice 7 + slice 8 = two → the `attendance/shared/`
   extraction (`loadRoster`, `resolveTermForDate`, `parseIsoDate`,
   `rateHundredths`, `fullName`, `TenantDb`, `STUDENT_NAME_SELECT`) is justified
   *now* (not at slice 7, when it had one).
4. **Default-false opt-in, tested via the manual lifecycle.** Seed off; manual
   scenario 1 toggles on. Avoids a non-default in the seed and exercises the
   real opt-in semantics in the cp2 gate.

## Opt-in semantics
Every subject endpoint calls `assertEnabled` FIRST (reads
`School.subjectAttendanceEnabled`; `schools` is not under RLS so it resolves
regardless of the tenant GUC) and 404s when off — even for owner/admin: the
surface genuinely doesn't exist for the school yet. The teacher portal learns
the flag via `/teacher-scope/me` (rides with `currentTerm`, since teachers can't
read school settings) so cp2 can hide the surface rather than 404 on click.

## Scope gate matrix (`assertCanMarkSubject`, on `getTeacherScope`)
owner/admin bypass · `subjectsByArm[arm]` includes subject → ✓ · in arm scope but
wrong subject (incl. a form teacher with no assignment) → **403** · arm out of
scope → **404**. Richer than assessment's uniform-404 `assertSubjectInScope`,
matching slice 7's daily 403/404 split.

